# restic-backup.sh configuration
#
# Copy this file to /etc/restic-backup.env (or any path you prefer, and
# pass it as the first argument to restic-backup.sh, or export it as
# RESTIC_BACKUP_CONFIG) and edit the values below.
#
# This file is sourced directly by bash, so it must be valid shell
# syntax: NAME=value, no spaces around "=", quote values containing
# spaces or special characters.
#
# Keep this file's permissions tight (e.g. `chmod 600`) since it
# references password files and, indirectly, your backup layout.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Core settings (all required)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Directory to back up.
BACKUP_SOURCE=/home/youruser

# Local restic repository. This is the "source of truth" repo that
# everything else gets copied FROM. Should live on its own disk/partition
# if at all possible, not the same disk as BACKUP_SOURCE.
LOCAL_REPO=/mnt/backup/restic-repo

# Scratch space for restic. Needs to be on a filesystem with enough free
# space for restic's temporary pack files (a few GB is typically plenty).
LOCAL_TMP=/mnt/backup/.restic-tmp

# File containing the restic repository password (plain text, one line,
# no trailing newline required either way). Keep this `chmod 600`,
# owned by root if the script runs as root.
LOCAL_PASSWORD_FILE=/etc/restic/local.pass

# Newline-separated restic exclude patterns. See:
# https://restic.readthedocs.io/en/stable/040_backup.html#excluding-files
EXCLUDE_FILE=/etc/restic/excludes.txt

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Optional settings (sane defaults shown)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# LOCK_FILE=/var/run/restic-backup.lock
# LOG_FILE=/var/log/restic-backup.log
# KEEP_DAILY=7
# RESTIC_TAG=daily
# RESTIC_HOST=$(hostname)   # NOTE: command substitution is NOT evaluated
#                           # in this file since it's sourced as plain
#                           # variable assignments -- if you want a
#                           # specific host tag, just write it literally,
#                           # e.g. RESTIC_HOST=myserver

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Targets
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Space-separated list of target names to run after the local backup.
# Leave empty (or comment out) to run local-only -- a reasonable starting
# point while you're first setting this up.
#
# Each name here must have a matching TARGET_<NAME>_* block below (NAME
# uppercased). Target names may only contain letters, digits, and
# underscores.

ENABLED_TARGETS="nas s3"

# --- Target: nas -------------------------------------------------------
# type=path: another restic repo reachable via a local filesystem path.
# Covers NAS shares (NFS/CIFS), another machine's disk exposed via a
# mount, a second local disk, etc. See README.md for a brief overview of
# setting up such a mount -- this script only checks it, it doesn't
# create it for you.

TARGET_NAS_TYPE=path
TARGET_NAS_REPO=/mnt/backup/nas-mount/restic-repo
# Optional: if set, checked with `mountpoint -q` before use. Omit this
# for a plain local path that's always available (e.g. a second internal
# disk that isn't a separate mount point).
TARGET_NAS_MOUNTPOINT=/mnt/backup/nas-mount
TARGET_NAS_PASSWORD_FILE=/etc/restic/nas.pass

# --- Target: s3 ----------------------------------------------------------
# type=s3: an S3-compatible object store -- Backblaze B2, AWS S3, MinIO,
# Wasabi, etc. See README.md for a pointer to restic's own S3/B2 backend
# docs and your provider's key-creation steps -- this script assumes you
# already have a bucket and an access key/secret pair.

TARGET_S3_TYPE=s3
# Restic's repository URL format for S3-compatible backends. Example
# shown is Backblaze B2's S3-compatible endpoint; adjust host/bucket for
# your provider.
TARGET_S3_REPO=s3:s3.us-east-005.backblazeb2.com/your-bucket-name
TARGET_S3_PASSWORD_FILE=/etc/restic/s3.pass
# A file that exports AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID and AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY (restic
# uses the same env vars as the AWS CLI for any S3-compatible backend).
# Example file contents:
#   export AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
#   export AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx
# Keep this file `chmod 600`.
TARGET_S3_ENV_FILE=/etc/restic/s3-credentials.env

# --- Add more targets by copying the pattern above --------------------
# e.g. a second offsite node reached via NFS:
#
# ENABLED_TARGETS="nas s3 offsite"
#
# TARGET_OFFSITE_TYPE=path
# TARGET_OFFSITE_REPO=/mnt/backup/offsite-mount/restic-repo
# TARGET_OFFSITE_MOUNTPOINT=/mnt/backup/offsite-mount
# TARGET_OFFSITE_PASSWORD_FILE=/etc/restic/offsite.pass

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Failure email (optional but recommended)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# Requires a `mail`-providing package (e.g. mailutils on Debian/Ubuntu)
# and a working local mail transport agent (e.g. postfix configured to
# relay outbound mail). See README.md for pointers -- this script does
# not configure mail delivery for you, it just calls `mail` if it's
# available.
#
# Leave MAIL_TO empty/unset to disable email notifications entirely; the
# script will still log everything to LOG_FILE.

# MAIL_TO=you@example.com
# MAIL_SUBJECT_TAG=[restic-backup]
